          "sequence": 75,
          "subtype": "message",
          "text": "Perfect! I've successfully localized the fault. Let me create a summary of my findings:\n\n## Fault Localization Summary\n\nI've identified the root cause of the HDA Intel sound driver failure after suspend to RAM:\n\n### **Buggy File**\n- `sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c`\n\n### **Buggy Functions**\n1. `azx_resume()` (line 2539) - System suspend/resume handler\n2. `azx_runtime_resume()` (line 2580) - Runtime PM resume handler\n\n### **Root Cause**\n\nThe bug occurs due to a missing reset of error-handling flags during device resume:\n\n1. **Error Handling Phase**: When codec communication timeouts occur, `azx_rirb_get_response()` progressively enables error-handling modes:\n   - Sets `polling_mode = 1` (line 912)\n   - Disables MSI (line 923)\n   - Sets `single_cmd = 1` (line 951) and calls `azx_free_cmd_io()` to disable CORB/RIRB\n\n2. **Suspend Phase**: `azx_suspend()` calls `azx_stop_chip()` which sets `initialized = 0`\n\n3. **Resume Phase** (THE BUG): `azx_resume()` and `azx_runtime_resume()` call `azx_init_chip()` to re-initialize, BUT:\n   - They do NOT reset `single_cmd`, `polling_mode`, or `poll_count` flags\n   - In `azx_init_chip()` at line 1222, there's a critical check: `if (!chip->single_cmd)`\n   - Since `single_cmd = 1` from error handling, CORB/RIRB is NOT re-initialized\n   - Device remains stuck in single_cmd mode, causing codec communication failures\n\n4. **Result**: Choppy audio with 2-second silences after resume. Only solution is reboot (which clears all state).\n\n### **Confidence: 0.95**\n\nThe result has been written to `/workspace/fault_localization_result.json`.",
